<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; SEASON FINALES ARE THE WEEK'S BIG DRAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE MARGULIES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Season-ending episodes brought larger than usual audiences to several TV 
dramas last week. But the opening installment of CBS' movie about the Menendez 
murders did not share in the windfall, A. C. Nielsen data showed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 ABC's "NYPD Blue" did best among the dramas, placing No. 5 among the week's 78 
prime-time network programs with an audience of about 15.7 million homes. "L.A. 
Law," completing its eight-season run on NBC, tied for No. 7 with ABC's "Home 
Improvement." And Fox's "Melrose Place" registered its biggest ratings ever to 
finish No. 18 nationally--and No. 4 locally. 
</P>
<P>
 Part 1 of CBS' "Menendez: A Killing in Beverly Hills" got clobbered on Sunday, 
however. With about 9 million homes tuning in, it finished at No. 46 and not 
only ranked well behind ABC's telecast of the hit movie "City Slickers" (No. 6) 
and NBC's movie "Seasons of the Heart" (No. 21), but also fell about 565,000 
homes short of the audience Fox got five weeks earlier for "Honor Thy Father 
and Mother: The True Story of the Menendez Murders." 
</P>
<P>
 Southland Ratings 
</P>
<P>
 Here are A. C. Nielsen's Top 10 prime-time programs in the Los Angeles area 
during the same week. Each rating point equals 50,064 households. 
