<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; MENTAL TEST ORDERED FOR KIDNAP SUSPECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DWAYNE BRAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A judge ordered a psychological evaluation for a Ventura man accused of 
kidnaping an auto salesman and leading police on a chase to Universal City -- 
and the defendant's attorney said his client will eagerly cooperate. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Public Defender Stephen P. Lipson said defendant Daryl Lynn Simpson 
believes he is Jesus and wants to tell the court-appointed psychologist his 
religious message. 
</P>
<P>
 Simpson, an unemployed 32-year-old oil-field worker, will probably change his 
not guilty plea to not guilty by reason of insanity, Lipson said. But Lipson 
said that would depend on the opinion of the doctor. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura County acting Superior Court Judge Bruce A. Clark ordered the 
psychological examination Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Police say Simpson was test-driving a black, $27,000 Camaro Z-28 from Paradise 
Chevrolet on Victoria Avenue earlier this month when he told a salesman that he 
was God and on his way to radio station KLOS in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 He drove south on the Ventura Freeway to the San Fernando Valley, police said. 
The salesman escaped when Simpson exited the freeway to make a phone call. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles police spotted the car in Van Nuys, triggering a chase where 
speeds reached 90 m.p.h. Simpson was finally arrested after the car he was 
driving hit a curb and got a flat tire. DWAYNE BRAY 
</P>
</TEXT>
