<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA SCHOOL PANEL VOTES TO BUY BUSINESS PARK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ventura school board on Tuesday approved spending nearly $5.7 million to 
purchase a large business park on Valentine Road near Victoria Avenue for its 
adult school program. 
</P>
<P>
 Board members voted unanimously to buy the Ventura Business Campus, two large 
office buildings at 5200 and 5280 Valentine Road. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ventura Unified School District's adult school plans to move its 
administrative offices and Technology Development Center, which has 300 
students, to the office complex in September, 1995. The school district is 
getting a deal on the property, officials said, because they are purchasing it 
from a realty group that foreclosed on the previous owner. 
</P>
<P>
 "It seems like a lot of money, " board member John Walker said. "But we're 
really getting a very, very good deal, not only for people right now in the 
district but also for their children in the years ahead." 
</P>
<P>
 The district will buy the office park for only $3.75 million, which officials 
said amounts to three-quarters of its current market value. In addition, the 
district will spend about $1.9 million on improvements. 
</P>
<P>
 The entire $5.7 million cost will be financed through privately issued bonds, 
called certificates of participation. The district will repay the bonds from 
adult-school tuition and lease payments from other tenants in the buildings. 
</P>
<P>
 The Technology Development Center, now split between two buildings on Dean and 
Palma drives, will occupy only part of the 5200 building. All of the tenants at 
5280 will be allowed to remain. 
</P>
<P>
 The entire adult school has about 8,500 students, most of whom attend classes 
at the Dean Drive campus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
