<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNION'S ENDING? YOU KEEP THE GIFTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELIZABETH MEHREN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For all of you whose impulse marriage was followed quickly by an impulse 
dissolution, here is today's social brain-scratcher: 
</P>
<P>
 What do you do with all the loot? 
</P>
<P>
 If people bring gifts to your hey-honey, let's-get-married wedding ceremony, 
or if they send presents soon thereafter, what happens when the union ends 
unhappily ever after? 
</P>
<P>
 Etiquette guru Judith Martin (also known as the author and syndicated 
columnist Miss Manners) says, basically, once you're married, the stuff is 
yours. "I do," in short, translates to "I keep" -- the gifts. 
</P>
<P>
 But, Martin adds: "This is not to discourage anyone who may be gracious enough 
to return the gifts." ELIZABETH MEHREN 
</P>
</TEXT>
